<li>Carr, Spencer, 1976. &lsquo;The Integrity of a Utilitarian,&rsquo;
<em>Ethics</em>, 86: 241&ndash;46.</li>

<li>Code, Lorraine, 1983. &ldquo;Father and Son: A Case Study in
Epistemic Responsibility&rdquo;, <em>Monist</em>, 66:
268&ndash;82.</li>

<li>Cottingham, John, 2010. &lsquo;Integrity and Fragmentation,&rsquo;
<em>Journal of Applied Philosophy</em>, 27: 2&ndash;14.</li>

<li>Cox, Damian, 2005. &lsquo;Integrity, Commitment and
Consequentialism,&rsquo; <em>Journal of Value Inquiry</em>, 39:
61&ndash;73.</li>

<li>Cox, Damian, La Caze, Marguerite and Levine, Michael P., 1999.
&lsquo;Should We Strive for Integrity?,&rsquo; <em>Journal of Value
Inquiry</em>, 33(4): 519&ndash;530.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2003. <em>Integrity and the Fragile
Self</em>, Aldershot: Ashgate.</li>

<li>Cox, Damian, Boaks, Jacqueline and Levine, Michael P., 2024,
&lsquo;Integrity and the University&rsquo;, <em>Philosophy of
Management</em>, 23(1): 109&ndash;124.</li>

<li>Davion, Victoria, 1991. &lsquo;Integrity and Radical
Change&rsquo;, in Claudia Card (ed.) <em>Feminist Ethics</em>,
Lawrence, Kansas: University of Kansas Press, pp. 180&ndash;192.</li>

<li>Dineen, Katy and Goff, Loretta, 2024. &lsquo;Two sides of the same
coin: a taxonomy of academic integrity and impropriety using
intellectual virtues and vices&rsquo;, <em>Assessment &amp;Evaluation
in Higher Education</em>, 49(7): 935&ndash;947.</li>

<li>Driver, Julia, 2012. <em>Consequentialism</em>, New York:
Routledge.</li>

<li>Dudzinski, Denise M., 2004. &lsquo;Integrity: Principled
Coherence, Virtue, or Both?&rsquo;, <em>Journal of Value Inquiry</em>,
38: 299&ndash;313.</li>

<li>Eliot, George, 1871 [1993]. <em>Middlemarch</em>, Ware, England:
Wordsworth Editions.</li>

<li>Enoch, D., 2006.&lsquo;Agency, Shmagency: Why Normativity
Won&rsquo;t Come From What is Constitutive of Agency,&rsquo;
<em>Philosophical Review</em>, 115: 169&ndash;198.</li>

<li>Eschenbach, Warren J., 2012, &lsquo;Integrity, Commitment, and a
Coherent Self&rsquo;, <em>Journal of Value Inquiry</em>, 46(3):
369&ndash;378.</li>

<li>Fornaroli, Giulio, 2019. &lsquo;Do We Need Integrity in a Theory
of Justice? A Critique of the &lsquo;Argument from Integrity&rsquo; in
Favour of Accommodations,&rsquo; <em>Journal of Applied
Philosophy</em>, 36(4): 659&ndash;674.</li>

<li>Frankfurt, Harry, 1971. &lsquo;Freedom of the Will and the Concept
of a Person,&rsquo; <em>Journal of Philosophy</em>, LXVIII:
5&ndash;20.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1987. &lsquo;Identification and
Wholeheartedness,&rsquo; in Ferdinand Schoeman (ed.)
<em>Responsibility, Character, and the Emotions: New Essays in Moral
Psychology</em>, New York: Cambridge University Press, pp.
27&ndash;45.</li>

<li>Gilligan, Carol, 1982. <em>In a Different Voice</em>, Cambridge,
MA: Harvard University Press.</li>

<li>Godlovitch, Stan, 1993. &lsquo;The Integrity of Musical
Performance&rsquo;, <em>Journal of Aesthetics and Art Criticism</em>,
51(4): 573&ndash;587.</li>

<li>Golden, Christian M., 2019. &lsquo;Taking Our Selves Too
Seriously: Commitment, Contestation, and the Dynamic Life of the
Self,&rsquo; <em>Southern Journal of Philosophy</em>, 57(4):
505&ndash;538.</li>

<li>Graham, Jody L., 2001. &lsquo;Does Integrity Require Moral
Goodness? <em>Ratio</em>, 14: 234&ndash;251.</li>

<li>Grant, Ruth W., 1997. <em>Hypocrisy and Integrity</em>, Chicago
and London: University of Chicago Press.</li>

<li>Haack, Susan, 1976. &lsquo;Concern for Truth: What it Means, Why
it Matters,&rsquo; <em>Annals-NY-Academy of Science</em>, 775:
57&ndash;63.</li>

<li>Halfon, Mark, 1989. <em>Integrity: A Philosophical Inquiry</em>,
Philadelphia: Temple University Press.</li>

<li>Harcourt, Edward, 1998. &lsquo;Integrity, Practical Deliberation
